popular imagination, from toxic spills and terrorism to plane crashes and pandemics. Along the way, he explores how the ubiquity of worst cases in everyday life has rendered them ordinary and mundane: very real threats like a killer flu or an American Hiroshima have become so common that they have lost their ability to shock us. Fear and dread, Clarke argues, have actually become too rare: only when the public has more substantial information and more credible warnings will it take worst cases as seriously as it should. A timely and necessary look into how we think about the unthinkable, Worst Cases will be must reading for anyone attuned to our current climate of threat and fear.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCatastrophical, The. 0aDisastersxPsychological aspects. 0aDisasters. 0aEmergency management. 0aRisk assessment. 0aTerrorismxPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aterror, catastrophe, fear, terrorism, toxic spills, destruction, annihilation, extinction, environmentalism, climate change, global warming, natural disasters, plane crashes, pandemic, warning, popular opinion, society, emergency management, disaster, risk assessment, nonfiction, history, psychology, sociology, politics, probabilism, power, panic, silver lining, worst case scenario, post apocalyptic.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226108605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226108605/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles